<TEXT>
a political adviser to president reagan 
described him in 1984 as a candidate who had run out of 
ammunition but whose strength was that he believed he couldnt be 
held responsible for his own administrations record according to 
a taperecorded account reported in a new book 
the book landslide by reporters jane mayer of the wall 
street journal and doyle mcmanus of the los angeles times 
describes a meeting of three reagan advisers on june 30 1984 in a 
conference room of reaganbush campaign headquarters 
the meeting was highly confidential the authors write 
but in this case the discussion was tape recorded and although 
the participants intended that the tapes stay secret they did 
not 
the authors do not say how they obtained the tapes which they 
say ran for four hours 
stuart spencer a veteran reagan strategist who chaired the 
meeting is quoted as saying at the outset the problem is weve 
been talking to everybody at the white house over the past few days 
and the reagan administration fired all its bullets very early 
and very successfully in the first two years 
all their plans all their priorities all their programs 
said spencer theyve run out of ammunition 
spencer is now an adviser to sen dan quayle of indiana running 
mate of republican presidential nominee george bush spencer did 
not immediately return a telephone call sunday seeking comment at 
his office in california 
later in that june 1984 meeting pollster robert teeter is 
quoted as saying that although reagan had run successfully as an 
outsider in 1980 you might have a problem people are beginning 
to believe that whats in place in washington is ronald reagans 
spencer whose association with reagan went back to his days as 
governor of california in the 1960s and 1970s replied he can 
pull it off in 1970 he pulled it off 
in his campaign for reelection as governor spencer argued 
reagan ran against the government he was running 
i mean he believes hes above it all said spencer he 
believes it thats why they believe it i cant believe it but 
they do 
according to the book the tape also shows the strategists 
seeking to overcome first lady nancy reagans resistance to having 
the president do a two or threeday campaign trip before the 
republican national convention in august 1984 
her reasoning is you dont put the actor onstage before the 
show starts spencer is quoted as saying she thinks the 
convention is the show i tried to make her see that youre talking 
about two different shows two different nights i think i finally 
got through to her 
the authors conclude that mrs reagan although the advisers did 
not know it evidently was relying on astrological advice her use 
of an astrologer was revealed earlier this year by former white 
house chief of staff donald t regan in his book for the 
record 
teeter is quoted as saying on the tape that advisers to reagans 
1984 opponent walter mondale were working on some examples that 
he reagan doesnt know what hes doing 
to counter this spencer suggested that the president give three 
or four sophisticated speeches in which he would talk about 
things like sound money constitutional reform education things 
that when he gets through people will think he sure as hell knows 
something without really saying something 
teeter also suggested presidential events with young people to 
help inoculate against the idea that he doesnt know whats going 
on 
as the advisers sought issues for the campaign the authors 
write the tapes show that spencer suggested reagan say something 
about acid rain and all that stuff because he was perceived as 
vulnerable on environmental issues 
speechwriter ken khachigian responded were better off 
without it if you get the old man going on it he does killer 
trees 
the killer trees phrase originated after reagan expressed 
the view in his 1980 campaign that trees cause air pollution 
the mayermcmanus book is published by houghton mifflin co 
</TEXT>
