<TEXT>
in a scene repeated throughout 
the country ethnic germans from eastern europe are crowding into 
the village of koenigstein in hopes of starting a new life in the 
west 
nearly 500 recently arrived ethnic germans are staying in 
koenigstein they are just a small part of a record wave of 200000 
expected to arrive in west germany this year 
most of them come from the soviet union and poland with smaller 
numbers from romania and other east european countries 
sure there are problems and difficulties says koenigstein 
mayor antonius weber our resources are overtaxed but the people 
are there and we have to do what we can he said in an interview 
in koenigstein 483 ethnic germans were crowded into two 
temporary housing facilities last week in this town of 16500 
nestled in the scenic taunus hills near frankfurt 
we simply cant refuse says weber of the new arrivals 
private initiatives are being started the zdf television 
network has announced it is setting up in conjunction with a 
nationwide charity organization a program to find private 
individuals willing to help the newcomers with the numerous 
problems they face 
the incorporation of several hundred thousand ethnic germans 
from eastern europe is one of the biggest challenges of the next 
few years zdf officials said in announcing the program 
officially the federal government welcomes the arrivals as 
german citizens and praises the soviet blocs increased willingness 
to permit their emigration centuries after their forebearers 
settled in parts of eastern europe 
but with red cross estimates saying the number will climb to 
600000 by the turn of the century many towns and cities are 
having trouble coping with the results of bonns opendoor policy 
after arriving at various transit camps such as friedland near 
the east german border the ethnic germans are gradually sent to 
other parts of west germany straining social services already 
kept busy with tens of thousands of asylumseekers from third world 
countries 
eventually the ethnic germans are given help to find their own 
housing and a job 
their difficulty understanding the german language has been a 
major problem especially since the children are required by law to 
attend school almost immediately after their arrival 
many of my colleagues tell me that in many towns and cities 
throughout the country the ethnic german chldren need extra 
