<TEXT>
congress is heading into the final weeks of 
its 1988 session talking optimistically but showing no overt action 
on its biggest piece of unfinished environmental business 
rewriting the clean air act 
its possible to get a good bill this year says rep john 
dingell dmich chairman of the energy and commerce committee 
where closeddoor negotiations on an antipollution package have 
been moving slowly 
in the senate george mitchell dmaine is more optimistic 
than hes ever been about getting floor time for a comprehensive 
bill that received environment committee approval more than a year 
ago says press secretary diane dewhirst 
house speaker jim wright dtexas and senate majority leader 
robert byrd dwva have clean air legislation on their short 
lists for possible floor debate as congress heads for adjournment 
by midoctober 
wright has not been a major player in drafting a blueprint to 
combat smog and other urban pollution into the next century and 
impose stiffer controls on acidrain pollution and airborne 
emissions of toxic chemicals 
byrd however is the principal factor in the senate impasse 
largely because of his interest in protecting his states coal 
industry which could lose business under a variety of acidrain 
control scenarios 
the lameduck majority leader has said little publicly about the 
situation on friday through press secretary tina evans he said 
theres a lot of pressure to deal with clean air legislation this 
year this is a very difficult and controversial issue and 
whether common ground can be found remains to be seen 
earlier friday wright was asked what byrd had told him about 
the legislations future in the senate this year hes hopeful he 
can steer it to a successful conclusion in the senate wright 
replied 
sources on both sides of the capitol say byrds major concerns 
are gaining more time for coalburning power plants and factories 
to clean up their emissions and providing some sort of economic 
cushion for mine workers hurt by any move away from coal caused by 
acid rain controls 
even the environmental protection agency is stepping up its 
involvement as adjournment nears epa administrator lee thomas who 
favors new efforts against urban pollution but opposes acid rain 
provisions is now telling lawmakers they should consider new 
provisions to control airborne pollutants 
from the lobbying sidelines the environmentalist clean air 
coalition and its rival the industrybacked clean air working 
group both say they want a bill this year but they are far apart 
on its contents 
coalition chairman richard ayres says his side wants the 
strongest bill it can get and wont hesitate to pull the plug on 
its push for a bill this year if the house and senate develop 
proposals too weak to clean up the air in this century 
the industry group opposes acid rain controls as premature and 
not supported by scientific consensus its administrator william 
fay says the group supports a prompt and sensible solution to 
urban pollution from carbon monoxide and smogproducing ozone 
at last count by epa about 100 cities and metropolitan areas 
were not complying with limits on these pollutants congress most 
likely remedy would be to give them more time to clean up but 
require tougher steps 
