slowmoving negotiations industry lobbyists point the finger at 
rep henry waxman dcalif the chairman of the energy and 
commerce health and the environment subcommittee an advocate of 
tough tailpipe emissions standards 
for their parts dingell and waxman are throwing no rocks at 
least in public sources close to the bargaining say the overall 
strategy is to mark time until it appears the senate will produce a 
bill before risking any unnecessary showdowns and bloodletting on 
the house side 
one thing the entire process cannot stand with time running out 
in 1988 is a contentious lengthy housesenate conference to 
resolve what likely would be major differences in legislation 
produced by each chamber 
mitchell and dingell have discussed ways of avoiding a rerun of 
1986 when they and others spent tortuous fractious months 
resolving house and senate bills to beef up the superfund 
hazardous waste cleanup program 
the two lawmakers reportedly have reached at least tentative 
agreement on steps to avoid a drawnout conference over clean air 
under the arrangement senate provisions on acid rain would form 
the starting point for conferees who would begin their 
negotiations over urban pollution provisions with what emerges from 
the house 
