<TEXT>
after 35 years henry clifford finally 
has his zamorano 80 and its not parked in his garage or orbiting 
saturn but sitting in a los angeles bank vault 
his zamorano 80 is one of just two complete collections of 80 
rare books declared by the los angelesbased zamorano club of 
bibliophiles in 1945 as works best representing early california 
history 
for more than four decades the collection of first editions has 
had cult following among book collectors a complete zamorano 80 is 
estimated to be worth between 750000 and 1 million 
the book club and the collection were named after agustin juan 
vicente zamorano who in the 19th century was californias first 
printer 
the books include such wellknown titles as mark twains 
roughing it and bret hartes the luck of roaring camp and 
more obscure works such as robert louis stevensons essays in the 
silverado squatters 
clifford 78 a retired investment counselor completed his 
collection this year when he bought the last two books for 42000 
the only other complete collection is at yale university the 
university of california berkeley has about 70 volumes and 
huntington library in san marino has 79 
the crown jewel of the collection no 80 missing from the 
huntington collection is a 90page work called the life and 
adventures of joaquin murieta the celebrated california bandit 
by john rollin ridge son of a cherokee chief 
only three or possibly four first editions are believed to 
exist clifford bought his more than 10 years ago from a private 
party in maine it was a bookbuying coup and ensured that it would 
only be a matter of time before he could complete his collection 
clifford plans to display his collection next year in san 
francisco new york or santa barbara and says that in the 
meantime anyone who wants to see it can contact me 
anyone that is except the huntington library 
the huntington has been hounding me for my collection but i 
wont give it to them said clifford a member of the librarys 
society of fellows which helps support the institution if 
things go to a library theyre buried with rare exception 
