<DOCNO> AP880919-0039 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
an idyllic patch of this new jersey 
borough provides a glimpse of what american suburbia could have 
been 
homes are arrayed in superblocks where residents share 
parks quiet culdesacs and a sense of community children often 
play unattended far from busy roads 
radburn a planned community started before the depression has 
gained worldwide renown but few imitators 
just 10 miles from the george washington bridge to new york 
city radburn stands as an anomaly among suburban tracts the 
149acre community has 500 singlefamily homes 48 townhouses 32 
duplexes and a 93unit apartment complex onetenth the size of 
the community planned by architects clarence stein and henry wright 
in the late 1920s 
it was to herald a new stage in development that relegated cars 
to peripheral streets and maintained serenity and social contact in 
residential life 
but the developer city housing corp went bankrupt during the 
depression and stopped building homes in radburn in 1936 
what remains is a comfortable novelty for 2800 residents and an 
enticing model of residential life for professional planners they 
say radburn has inspired some imitations in india england france 
and in a few us communities including reston va in 1974 the 
site was included in the national register of historic places 
it certainly stands out as an oasis within the typical 
tracthouse suburbia that surrounds it said james w hughes 
chairman of the department of urban planning and policy development 
at rutgers university it sort of reverses the traditional 
pattern of suburban houses fronting on the streets 
hughes said architects stein and wright were involved with the 
garden city movement which sought to counteract the congestion 
in urban areas in northern new jersey and new york early this 
century 
in terms of the history of planning its extremely 
significant hughes said essentially it was the first town 
that was attempted to be built for the motor age supposedly to 
tame the automobile 
radburn the name means saddle river in old english after the 
nearby river of that name was innovative in its approach to 
residential block design 
the creators abandoned the traditional gridiron street pattern 
in favor of the superblock a large block of land surrounded by 
main roads the houses mostly colonial and english tudor style 
are grouped around culdesacs served by narrow access roads 
coming from main roads the land inside the area consists of parks 
living and sleeping sections in the houses face the park and garden 
areas service rooms such as the kitchen face the access road 
it envisioned a planned decentralization in american 
society said robert fishman who describes radburn as a model 
community in his book bourgeois utopias the rise and fall of 
suburbia 
the radburn community was to be the center of a whole region 
based on a decentralization of housing and also of industry 
fishman said it would return america to a communitybased life 
that is absent today 
the community is financed by its residents who pay a charge 
based on their propertys assessed valuation residents also pay 
the full borough tax rate radburn fees which go to an 
administrative body called the radburn association pay for the 
maintenance of property and recreation programs 
the association manages a park network of 23 acres two swimming 
pools four tennis courts four baseball fields and three 
playground areas 
an elementary school and a nondenominational church are located 
on the borders of the property most radburn children can reach the 
school without crossing a road 
ernest morris a radburn resident for 36 years pays 3000 
annually in borough taxes and 700 to the association which he 
considers a bargain for a place that he has always considered 
special 
its become an ideal community for senior citizens in that 
everything is within walking distance he said 
the community comprises mainly senior citizens and young 
professionals a big reason price the radburn homes that once 
sold for about 6000 average more than 200000 when they are 
available said ron gatti manager of the association 
planners say that radburn could not be recreated today except 
in very expensive developments but they say the trend toward 
clustered housing and condominium developments in the northeast has 
begun to replicate some of the communal radburn residents feel 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

