<TEXT>
for many texas ranchers hurricane 
gilbert may turn out to be what the bankers have ordered 
the hurricane looked for a time as if it might storm its way 
into the hill country and leave a trail of flooding and 
winddamaged property 
instead the storm broke up mostly into a series of gentle fall 
rains that officials say will boost agricultural prospects in the 
southwestern part of the state 
it was just about what we wanted perfect so far said 
don mathis director of a farmers home administration district that 
governs federal agricultural lending in 26 counties in central 
texas hill country and in the western part of the state 
most of the territory already has gotten from 2 to 5 inches 
of rain mathis said sunday if a lot of these people hadnt 
gotten rain they would have had to sell off a lot of their basic 
herd and practically start all over 
until gilberts rains mathis said a drought situation was 
getting critical 
mathis said he will attend a meeting early this week in oklahoma 
city at which adminstration officials will update farm lending 
policies a lack of rain earlier this month had been threatening to 
set back what had been a modest economic recovery during the past 
two years he said 
evidence of the rainfall shortage could be seen during the past 
two weeks at livestock houses mathis said many ranchers whose 
grazing land was running thin began dumping sheep and goats in 
record numbers at junction and san angelo he said 
calf sales also were approaching records although many of them 
were not being sold at ideal weights mathis said ranchers simply 
decided it was more lucrative to sell them now than to purchase 
grain and fatten them 
this rain makes a lot of difference he said its going 
to mean the ranchers wont have to buy as much hay for their 
livestock this winter 
the economic impact wont stop at ranch property lines mathis 
said 
its going to make a difference in all our area mathis 
said in many of our little towns not losing that cash flow is 
going to mean a lot 
weather officials said more rain could fall in the hill country 
and parts of west texas as what at one time was the most intense 
hurricane on record continued to break up and stall against a cold 
front encroaching from the northwest 
