a beijing court cleared a newspaper of libel for 
reporting unsanitary conditions in a factory and chinese 
journalists said monday they hope a precedent has been set for 
press freedom 
the official englishlanguage china daily said the case was 
followed closely by chinese reporters because the country does not 
yet have a law stipulating the rights and responsibilities of 
newspapers 
the xinyuanzhai beverage factory of beijing claimed it lost 
160000 in business after the beijing evening news reported in 
july the city was fining it for poor sanitation and flies the 
factory director chang jiangqiu said the story was erroneous 
because he had not paid a fine when the story was published he 
also said the factory did not have flies 
after a sixhour trial last week beijings eastern district 
court said the paper had made only a minor technical error and 
that this was not enough to support a defamation claim china 
daily reported 
the court rejected the factorys demand for 13000 in damages 
and ordered it to pay a 5 trial fee the factory has not said if 
it will appeal 
as part of recent political and economic reforms the chinese 
media have been allowed to investigate and report disasters 
scandals and corruption as well as cases of consumer abuse that 
were previously offlimits 
one result been an increase in the number of legal complaints 
against papers and journalists 
the beijing evening news said it reported on the factorys 
failings to fulfill its responsibility as a consumer watchdog a 
new role for chinas tightly controlled official press 
this is the first libel case actually brought to court against 
a paper said wu jingshu a national news editor at the china 
daily other cases have been settled through mediation he said 
adding journalists think that papers need something to protect 
them people can sue for anything 
the china daily quoted the beijing evening news deputy chief 
editor liu tingzhao as saying the case illustrated the urgent 
need for a journalism law 
legislators began drafting a law in 1984 to codify the rights 
and responsibilities of journalists including the right to 
criticize government officials the law is not yet completed 
