a new interfaith cable tv network went on the 
air monday offering a variety of music drama documentaries and 
magazinestyle shows 
originating from quarters at lower manhattans trinity episcopal 
church and broadcast through uplink facilities on long island 
visns programming is being carried by several major cable 
companies its founders say 
its going to give a more rounded picture of what religious 
life is all about said the rev wilford v bane jr interim 
general manager of the new network 
other religious tv operations have been rather 
singledimensional he said and havent reflected the mainstream 
of religion in america 
visn which stands for vision interfaith satellite network is a 
cooperative venture of 19 denominations protestant roman 
catholic eastern orthodox jewish and mormon 
it has signed contracts with 10 of the countrys largest cable 
system owners operating several cable companies each they 
represent a potential viewing audience of 18 million subscriber 
homes bane said 
we have started with big multisystem owners and have relied 
on them to get their individual cable systems on line he said 
he estimated the programming in the initial weeks may be 
available only to about 6 million households since some local 
systems will need time to adjust schedules to carry it 
at the outset the network is on the air in limited periods of 
five hours on weekdays 1 pm to 6 pm edt and longer on 
weekends from 7 am to 5 pm saturdays and 6 am to 5 pm 
sundays 
it expects to go to 12hour daily schedules by the first of the 
year including prime time 
bane a united methodist said the content in its varied forms 
would be oriented to religiousmoral questions that people meet in 
their everyday lives 
once the extent of subscribers is determined the network 
intends to seek commercial sponsors as well as contributions from 
foundations to provide financing to expand production 
however unlike much religious programming the network will not 
solicit contributions 
from the outset fees the cable industry pays to carry the 
network are expected to cover central operating costs of about 6 
million annually 
the 19 denominations are supplying an estimated 40 percent of 
the programs and underwriting their production costs a main 
financial item some programs are being acquired and others are to 
be jointly produced by visn 
the first days programming mostly in half hour segments 
included 
westbrook hospital a drama produced by the sevenday 
adventists man alive a documentary obtained from the canadian 
broadcasting system catch the spirit a magazinetype show 
produced by united methodists 
also christopher closeups a roman catholic interview show 
