<TEXT>
the army said monday it was 
scaling back plans for a laboratory in western utah for testing 
germ warfare defenses 
the armys plans for the biological laboratory at dugway proving 
ground had drawn strong opposition from utahs governor and 
congressional delegation and from opponents of research into 
genetically altered organisms 
the army initially proposed a 54 million biological aerosol 
test facility with the highest level of containment possible 
biosafety level 4 such a facility is required for experiments 
involving genetically altered organisms and diseases for which 
there are no vaccines 
the army said it had no plans to conduct tests involving such 
organisms at the dugway facility but it wanted the ability to do 
so if the need arose 
at a news conference monday michael owen deputy assistant 
secretary of the army for installation and logistics said the army 
would instead seek to build a 5 million level 3 test facility in 
1991 
level 3 testing involves diseases for which cures exist 
the armys decision is based on an extensive evaluation of the 
requirements for biological defense owen said existing army 
bl4 facilities will be used to satisfy any future needs for 
material testing that requires a containment level higher than 
bl3 
the new laboratory would replace an older facility at the 
western utah desert army installation 70 miles southwest of salt 
lake city it would be used to test procedures developed for 
defense against an attack with biological materials the united 
states is party to a 1972 treaty that prohibits the offensive use 
of biological agents 
biological testing has been conducted at dugway since 1952 
the announcement was greeted with enthusiasm by gov norm 
bangerter and utahs congressional delegation who joined owen at 
the news conference 
i think its a good idea of cooperation between the citizens 
between the governors office between the delegation and the army 
which took it upon themselves to back down considerably on this 
effort said rep james hansen rutah 
