<TEXT>
trevor pinnocks debut as an operatic conductor 
at the metropolitan opera has already raised eyebrows but the 
british early music specialist says youve got to start 
somewhere why not here 
pinnock will conduct handels giulio cesare which premieres 
tuesday with kathleen battle as cleopatra and tatiana troyanos as 
caesar jeffrey walker in the role of ptolemy is the first 
countertenor male alto to appear at the met 
the more significant first for the met is having an early music 
specialist in the pit pinnock who founded and directs the english 
concert is one of britains bestknown workers in the original 
instruments field along with christopher hogwood and john eliot 
gardner 
however the announcement that pinnock would conduct giulio 
cesare provoked some critical grousing last season donal 
henahan chief music critic of the new york times ended a 
laudatory review of one of pinnocks performances with this warning 
shot followers of the metropolitan opera must wonder what 
qualifies mr pinnock to conduct next seasons julius caesar 
the trouble is people are always ready to pigeonhole 
everybody pinnock said before rehearsal recently 
ive done giulio cesare ive done it with students on stage 
in london but the fact is ive never conducted in an opera house 
before he said 
i do know the music through and through i love the music of 
handel and i love working with singers in a certain way all 
music is sung i hate music that doesnt breathe 
pinnock 41 has been performing professionally since 1966 and 
he formed the english concert in 1973 
the met has only been doing handel since 1983 when rinaldo 
entered the repertory followed by an operatic version of the 
oratorio samson in 1985 
this production of giulio cesare was done by john copley for 
the english national opera in 1978 with charles mackerras 
conducting 
pinnock is not working with original instruments at the met but 
with a small orchestra 18 violins six cellos three basses and 
harpsichord of modern instruments 
the early music influence will come in the style of playing 
especially the ornamentation in both the instrumental and vocal 
parts 
of course it has been paramount in my musical considerations 
the combination of what handel wants and how to fill the hall 
pinnock said 
its interesting how much thats affected ornamentation i 
have quite strong ideas about the type of ornamentation that is 
suitable for a large space as opposed to a small room i think the 
ornamentation in general needs more space it cant be tight and 
fast ornamentation 
it also has to suit the voice 
ive found that ive had to write quite different 
ornamentation in some cases for cover singers pinnock said 
because obviously one is trying to solve two things in 
ornamentation first and foremost for me ones trying to enhance 
the meaning of the words and the whole sense of the aria if the 
ornamentation doesnt do that its completely wasted notes 
secondly it is to show off the voice and it must be to show off 
the beautiful qualities of whoever is singing it 
giulio cesare premiered in london in 1724 and was revised 
and revived in 1725 1730 and 1732 following its last german 
performances in 1733 it disappeared from the repertory until the 
1920s 
restoring the reputation of handels more than three dozen 
operas has become a cause for his partisans winton dean and john 
merrill knapp in a monumental scholarly survey of handels operas 
published last year contended that handel ranks with monteverdi 
mozart and verdi among the supreme masters of opera 
pinnock said handels operas have unfairly gained a reputation 
for being static that has something to do with the limitations of 
the opera seria form of recitatives mixed with da capo 
arias solos which have two movements repeating the first 
pinnock sees giulio cesare as a series of pictures in which 
the audience is invited to take part 
the da capo aria musically enhances the meaning of the 
words he said so what weve begun to understand in the 
beginning weve entered the picture then were fully in 
accordance with whats being sung and can relish the atmosphere 
before moving on to the next picture 
now of course it is possible in a certain production to make 
it so static that we as the audience are not invited in but i 
believe that the good production of a handel opera will at the same 
time honor that concept of the picture and not destroy it by 
ridiculous movement 
among pinnocks future projects is next seasons launching of 
the classical band in new york an original instruments 
orchestra of 40 or 50 players which will have guest conductors 
leonard bernstein wants to have a go pinnock said though 
thats not yet definite 
he says he wants to be free to perform any kind of music though 
pinnock admits some limitations 
im not good enough at playing jazz which upsets me a lot 
because i feel i should be but i dont know the language well 
enough 
ive always held that at their best moments the bands of basie 
and ellington showed how a band should work and thats the same 
sort of basis as my little orchestra the english concert 
as a director one has to set up the best framework for the 
individual musicians to play even better than they know how that 
was the great art of count basie who didnt always have the 
greatest soloists but he often managed to make it possible for 
them to play even better than one would expect 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0175 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
suzhou is the name of a nearby city of 
gardens known for its beauty it also is the name of a creek in 
shanghai known for its ugliness 
suzhou creek whose waters once abounded in clams and crabs and 
were prized by ancient winemakers today is shanghais most glaring 
symbol of a pollution problem that endangers the health of its 12 
million citizens 
officials fear the creeks pollution and stench also could scare 
off foreigners willing to invest in the rebirth of shanghai as a 
leading center of industry and commerce 
but the government has begun to act 
construction began in august of a 432million pipeline project 
to divert the raw sewage now discharged into suzhou creek and 
flowing into the huangpu river shanghais main waterway 
qiu xingyan chief engineer of the pollution control division in 
the citys environmental protection bureau said the system will 
transport the garbage into the yangtze river estuary north of 
chinas largest city 
i was a little worried at first about shifting pollution from 
the suzhou to the yangtze qiu said in an interview but stressed 
that the sewage will be treated and wont affect water quality in 
the yangtze 
shanghai last year completed a 162million project to move 
treatment stations for the citys drinking water into less 
contaminated waters further up the huangpu river 
raw garbage still flows into water used for drinking and more 
money must be spent in the future to move water stations upstream 
but there has been an improvement over the recent past when every 
glass of drinking water was onethird chlorinated sewage 
during the song dynasty 9601279 winemakers used water from 
the suzhou then called the wusong for highquality wine but by 
the 1920s with shanghai fast rising as the commercial and 
industrial center of china the river was already badly polluted 
its fish and crabs dying off 
today the 77mile river snakes through industrial workingclass 
neighborhoods of shanghai finally dumping the refuse of textile 
and chemical factories into the huangpu along the citys famed 
waterfront bund 
in contrast to the deathlike dun of its surface the suzhou 
churns with activity hundreds of flatboats ply the waters loading 
clothing and shoes some bound for overseas markets and unloading 
televisions and other consumer goods 
the fumes from old trucks compete with the odors wafting from 
the river suzhou creek is only the most pungent example of 
shanghais water pollution problems regarded as the worst in china 
zhang mingyo of the city environmental protection research 
institute said shanghais 10000 factories every day dump 5 million 
tons of largely untreated sewage into branches of the huangpu 
city environmentalists even keep tabs of the stink factor on 
the huangpu and last year the river registered 150 foulsmelling 
days 
more seriously scientists believe shanghais high rates of 
stomach liver and esophagal cancer are linked to poor water 
quality in the first half of this year 30 people died and 300000 
were sickened from a major outbreak of hepatitis in the city caused 
by contaminated clams 
the experts acknowledge that the pollution problem in shanghai 
became worse after the communist takeover in 1949 and has become 
even more serious with chinas economic takeoff in the 1980s 
the state environmental protection bureau has estimated that 
more than 29000 miles of chinas waterways have been contaminated 
by industrial pollution although environmental protection laws 
have been enacted the state lacks both the money for pollution 
controls and the will to slow the pace of the nations 
modernization drive 
estimates are that shanghai already reeling from the costs of 
rebuilding its antiquated industries and woefully inadequate 
infrastructure will need 4 billion by the turn of the century to 
reach national standards on water and air pollution 
the city now fines factories that exceed limits on the density 
of the garbage they discharge although it does not regulate the 
amount of sewage released it will also charge fees for use of the 
new suzhou pipeline and others planned to be built by the year 
2000 the pollution control divisions qiu said 
qiu added the new pipeline will handle only 40 percent of the 
sewage now discharged into the suzhou 
but he said the city plans to eliminate the smell by the year 
2000 and hopes that one day fish will return to the suzhou 
the project is important to shanghai he said because 
foreigners who see and smell suzhou creek may be reluctant to 
invest in the citys development 
cleaning up the creek he said will be helpful for the image 
of shanghai 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

