<TEXT>
working from a plywood shack 
and a collection of tents perched on the flank of augustine 
volcano researchers are setting up a hightech system to measure 
the volcanos shudders to within an inch 
when theyre done scientists using briefcasesized laser 
instruments could detect less than that but its a matter of 
whether you believe it says gene iwatsubo of the us geological 
survey one of the researchers trying to puzzle out how the volcano 
works and whether its eruptions can be predicted 
the thrust of the research is to try to find precursors signs 
of eruption says juergen kienle a university of alaska 
geophysics professor the more precursors you have the better 
off you are 
augustine volcano juts 4000 feet out of kamishak bay on the 
west side of cook inlet it appears benign but there have been six 
major eruptions since its discovery in 1778 one in 1883 
triggered a 30foot wave that destroyed houses and boats at port 
graham nearly 50 miles away 
computer models show a slidegenerated tsunami would reach 
homer a kachemak bay fishing community of 4000 people about 70 
miles away in about an hour a smaller wave would reach anchorage 
175 miles away three hours later 
we cant assess the probability of a slide occurring says 
state seismologist john davies all were saying is there is a 
possiblity we have no way to calculate the likelihood but if we 
cant calculate the possibility we feel its best to monitor it 
information that may enable scientists to predict eruptions 
accurately at augustine may be of great value to other parts of the 
world where millions of people live in the shadows of volcanoes 
or on them 
if you tell a mayor there is a 5 percent chance his town will 
be wiped out its hard for him to take action davies says if 
you tell him theres a 75 percent chance his town is going to be 
wiped out he can act 
kienle and seven researchers from the university of alaska 
geophysical institute and usgs have been pounding in benchmarks and 
performing surveys and gas studies a 100000 effort by the 
statefederal cooperative alaska volcano observatory formed this 
year a magnetic study also is planned 
this is really an uncomplicated volcano kienle says this 
one is really easy to deal with its very beautiful very active 
augustine the most active of some 60 volcanoes in the aleutian 
arc erupted in 1812 1883 1935 1964 1976 and 1986 when it 
spewed ash over much of southcentral alaska disrupting air 
traffic 
seismographs sensitive enough to detect passing planes nearby 
boats and high winds were placed on the volcano in 1970 their 
tracings on machines in fairbanks mapped the 1976 eruption and the 
eight months of seismic activity before the eruption 10 years later 
in january and february of 1986 scientists began briefing the 
air force federal aviation administration and state division of 
emergency services about a possible eruption early march 26 the 
seismographs showed earthquakes at the rate of about 50 per day 
within hours the rate to 500 then 5000 augustine blew its top 
the next day 
its a constant process of becoming better at forecasting when 
the volcano will become active kienle says we are getting 
better we will continue to get better 
four seismographs ring the volcano at an elevation of about 
1000 feet and two are near the peak three sets of tiltmeters 
measure changes in the surface 
one of the things were discovering is that most volcanoes 
have their own uniqueness davies says not every detail that 
one learns at one volcano is applicable to another its the 
hopeful assumption that you can apply it elsewhere i dont think 
it is a longshot hope i think its likely 
the value is obvious 
</TEXT>
