compensation for the 1984 gas disaster that killed 2800 people and 
injured more than 20000 
bhopal district judge mw deo reset the hearing for oct 1 
after both sides said the supreme court had yet to rule on appeals 
for interim relief to those injured in the worlds worst industrial 
accident 
the indian government is contesting a high court ruling that 
reduced interim relief from 35 billion rupees 270 million to 
25 billion rupees 192 million 
union carbide is challenging both awards saying the courts 
cannot order relief payment until responsibility for the leak has 
been determined 
a decision on the appeals is expected within a week advocate 
general am mathur told the judge 
the disaster occurred on dec 3 1984 when toxic methyl 
isocyanate gas leaked from the pesticide plant operated by union 
carbides indian subsidiary 
the government filed the lawsuit against union carbide in bhopal 
district court in 1986 after passing a law making it the sole 
representative of all the victims 
the government claims the accident was caused by negligence and 
filed criminal charges against seven carbide officials union 
carbide maintains the leak was due to sabotage by a disgruntled 
employee 
the government also has presented copies of claims filed by more 
than 5000 people injured in the accident and has asked the court 
to order union carbide to produce a copy of its insurance policy 
union carbide based in danbury conn earlier said it could 
not be sued because the bhopal plant was run by its subsidiary 
union carbide india ltd the government contends the insurance 
policy will prove that union carbide controlled the plant and 
therefore should pay compensation to the victims 
