<TEXT>
how many junior executives does it take 
to cross a stream with three wobbly boards 
about a dozen but wait till you try 
imagine getting a team of aggressive independentthinkers to 
stop overanalyzing the situation long enough to scramble across 
the creek in 20 minutes 
thats the mission of one outward bound exercise that comes with 
a package of adventure training here in the rocky mountains 
the creek crossing is part of a day of problem solving 
designed to force participants to work as a team in a rough very 
rough equivalent of a business crisis 
one team of managers that recently attempted the socalled 
acid river test included this reporter drafted by the 
associated press to experience the training firsthand 
our team made up of managers from a number of different 
companies ventured to the streams edge with another group from 
the champion spark plug co 
my group consisted of three people who ran their own businesses 
including a grandmother plus an insurance salesman two 
educators two program directors for philanthropic organizations a 
securities lawyer a utility executive and the chief operating 
officer of a gas pipeline company 
each team was given three boards which we could use to reach 
blocks strategically placed in the water if any board touched the 
water we had to forfeit it 
whats worse we had to bring the boards with us as we went 
since the boards werent long enough to simply lay end to end 
across the stream and if anyone fell into the water they would be 
penalized by being forced to wear a blindfold 
our team leader a woman in her late 20s was confounded like 
the rest of us while she was open to suggestions the route to dry 
ground proved more anguishing than a threeaspirin meeting with the 
boss 
first there was silence then frustration a sprinkling of 
debate and finally anxiety 
you have 10 minutes left shouted the instructors 
we quickly consigned an insurance salesman from florida to be 
our advance man since he seemed most fit and least likely to 
lose the boards in the drink as we experimented with different 
jerryrigged configurations 
the minutes clicked by though and it seemed obvious we just 
didnt have enough boards some of us were ready to give up 
the key came first to a woman who runs her own consulting 
business she saw that two boards placed in a tpattern would reach 
the blocks and allow us to complete a makeshift bridge with the 
third board 
grabbing each others shoulders or hands for support our group 
made it across with a few seconds left and yelped in triumph like a 
pack of day campers 
looking back on it there was no single leader no strategy by 
decree everyone did something to contribute in retrospect the 
solution seemed surprisingly obvious 
some of us also took comfort in the fact that the champion spark 
plug group got eaten by the acid 
</TEXT>
