<TEXT>
for a nation accustomed to enormous debts in its 
consumer business and government sectors the idea of 
trilliondollar social security surpluses tends to sound like a 
financial fairy tale 
the idea of a surplus anywhere in uncle sams books would be 
hard to accept but to believe that it will appear in the social 
security account just recently rescued from insolvency sounds 
utterly implausible 
but implausibility gets strained further the surplus talked 
about is in amounts almost incomprehensible not just to ordinary 
folks who have a difficult time adjusting to millions of dollars 
but even to actuaries 
as calculated by the social security administration the surplus 
could grow to 12 trillion in about 40 years and since the 
surplus would have to be invested in treasury securities it might 
absorb the entire national debt 
the scenario becomes more incredible with the federal deficit 
vanished a string of surplus years might occur in the next 
century forcing interest rates down and conceivably spurring or 
retarding economic growth 
but there is another side to the story too and it adds to the 
incredible nature of this financial phenomenon is it possible for 
highly trained actuaries to make multitrilliondollar errors could 
all this be a dream 
there are those who say it is writing for the heritage 
foundation a conservative think tank professor peter j ferrara 
of george mason law school calls the projections the great social 
security surplus hoax 
the trouble is that there is and will be no cash mountain 
he says those who think there will be have been misreading us 
government social security projections and do not understand 
federal budget accounting 
a study by donaldson lufkin amp jenrette a securities firm 
questions some underlying assumptions it claims estimates are 
based on an absence of recessions mortality rates that improve too 
slowly and an uninterrupted and unlikely increase in real wages 
of 14 percent a year 
in fact the social security administration itself offers a 
pessimistic scenario of slow growth and relatively high inflation 
that has the surplus peaking at 33 trillion in 2015 rather than 
at 12 trillion in the year 2030 
thats a difference of 87 trillion 
in the view of some who view the entire surplus projection as a 
pipe dream the huge range in official estimates demonstrates that 
sensible people should retreat from the future to more practical 
problems of the moment 
generally these critics argue that the projections are based on 
invalid assumptions regarding demographics health income 
interest rates fertility rates and a dozen other considerations 
many of them economic and political 
moreover they point out even if the surplus does accumulate to 
12 trillion by 2030 it might all disappear in payments to 
recipients over the following two decades that is any surplus 
would be temporary 
still critics say repeatedly politicians cannot be trusted to 
keep their hands off any pile of money inevitably it is said 
they would devise ways to spend it if you do not believe it they 
say you deserve to be hoaxed 
not taking any chances howard stein chairman of dreyfus corp 
commissioned a study of what an end to federal deficits might mean 
for investors to begin with longterm bonds would appear to be 
an extraordinary value 
an editorial in a newsletter for investors in dreyfus mutual 
funds this month warned there will be all sorts of ingenious 
proposals for diverting this money to worthy programs 
buttressed by equally ingenious arguments 
it reminded readers it really isnt the governments money 
it belongs to every working american man and woman today and in 
the future it suggested they be vigilant 
