<DOCNO> AP880919-0295 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal judge on monday ordered the loreal 
cosmetic company to pay 21 million to an illinois hair care 
business for copyright infringement and barred the french 
corporation from selling its zazu line of products in the 
united states 
were happy to have this verdict said james fitzgibbon the 
attorney for zazu designs a hinsdale illbased hair salon that 
also manufacturers and sells hair care products this was a case 
where the evidence unquestionably supported the findings 
in a 26page decision us district judge prentice marshall 
ruled that parisbased loreal took an arbitrary exciting mark 
which belonged to plaintiff and destroyed it 
it regarded plaintiff zazu as a small town nuisance 
marshall said 
he ordered loreal to pay zazu designs 100000 for lost 
profits 1 million to help the firm restore the trademark and 1 
million in punitive damages 
the judge also ordered loreal to stop selling its zazu products 
and ordered the firm to remove them from store shelves around the 
country 
neither loreal officials nor their attorneys could be reached 
for comment on the ruling monday night no one answered at the 
offices of the companys new york attorney russell falconer 
loreal had moved to dismiss the case on grounds that it was not 
subject to the jurisdiction of the northern illinois district 
court marshall noted but he said the motion was denied because 
defendant loreal is present in this district and has committed 
the wrongful acts attributed to it in this district 
zazu designs hair salon was founded in 1979 by raymond koubek 
and salvatore segretto and the name was registered with illinois 
authorities 
the store quickly became known in the chicago area and its 
revenue increased from 40000 the first year to 450000 in 1986 
and 600000 in 1987 according to court documents 
koubek and segretto represent the great american dream 
marshall wrote in his decision they have taken their skills 
undergone extensive training and emerged as very successful 
entrepreneurs in a highly competitive business 
in 1985 koubek and segretto began selling hair care products 
bearing the zazu trademark the same year loreal began planning 
its line of hair cosmetics a year later loreal chose zazu as the 
name for its new products court records showed 
in their investigation into whether the trademark was available 
loreal officials called zazu designs but did not speak to the two 
owners all that was asked was whether zazu products were sold at 
the store the judge said 
the investigation was perfunctory cursory and of little or 
no value marshall said plaintiff zazu was looked upon as a 
nettlesome fly to be brushed aside despite the fact that it had 
registered the mark zazu in the very industry that defendant 
intended to enter under that identical name 
</TEXT>
